  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ollama is a local model runtime that wraps llama.cpp with a user-friendly CLI and an HTTP API designed to look like OpenAI's. It handles model download, storage, GPU layer allocation, and serves inference via a daemon you run on your own machine. The primary reasons to choose Ollama over a cloud API are "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "data privacy"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (no data leaves the machine), "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "offline operation"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "zero per-token cost"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " after the hardware is provisioned. The trade-off is lower throughput than cloud inference, a hard VRAM cap on model size, and no built-in scaling."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Architecture Overview"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Ollama architecture diagram showing the model registry on the left, the Ollama daemon in the center with local model storage, llama.cpp runtime with GPU layer allocation, and an HTTP API layer, then client integrations on the right including the Python SDK, OpenAI-compatible client, LangChain, curl, and IDE extensions, and a Modelfile customization panel for system prompts, inference parameters, and LoRA adapters, with a hardware tier comparison at the bottom"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Installation and First Run"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ollama installs as a single binary that starts a background daemon. On macOS and Linux, the daemon runs as a user service; on Windows, it runs as a background process."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# macOS / Linux: one-line install\ncurl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh\n\n# Pull and run a model interactively\nollama run llama3.2\n\n# Pull only (no interactive shell)\nollama pull mistral\nollama pull codellama:13b          # specific size variant\nollama pull qwen2.5:7b-instruct   # specific tag\n\n# List downloaded models\nollama list\n\n# Inspect a model's metadata\nollama show llama3.2\n\n# Start/stop the daemon manually (usually not needed)\nollama serve          # starts on port 11434\nOLLAMA_HOST=0.0.0.0:11434 ollama serve  # listen on all interfaces (caution on public machines)\n\n# Check daemon is running\ncurl http://localhost:11434/api/tags"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Python SDK"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "ollama"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " Python package wraps the HTTP API with a typed interface that mirrors the Anthropic and OpenAI clients. Both synchronous and async variants are provided."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install ollama\nimport ollama\n\n# Simple completion\nresponse = ollama.generate(\n    model=\"llama3.2\",\n    prompt=\"Explain gradient descent in two sentences.\",\n)\nprint(response[\"response\"])\n\n# Chat with message history\nresponse = ollama.chat(\n    model=\"llama3.2\",\n    messages=[\n        {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"What is 2 + 2?\"},\n    ],\n)\nprint(response[\"message\"][\"content\"])\n\n# Streaming — yields chunks as they arrive\nfor chunk in ollama.generate(\n    model=\"llama3.2\",\n    prompt=\"List 5 Python best practices.\",\n    stream=True,\n):\n    print(chunk[\"response\"], end=\"\", flush=True)\n\n# Custom options (inference parameters)\nresponse = ollama.generate(\n    model=\"llama3.2\",\n    prompt=\"Write a haiku about Python.\",\n    options={\n        \"temperature\": 0.9,\n        \"top_p\": 0.9,\n        \"num_ctx\": 4096,       # context window size\n        \"num_predict\": 128,    # max tokens to generate\n        \"stop\": [\"\\n\\n\"],      # stop sequences\n    },\n)\n\n# List available models\nmodels = ollama.list()\nfor m in models[\"models\"]:\n    print(m[\"name\"], m[\"size\"])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OpenAI-Compatible Client"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ollama exposes an OpenAI-compatible endpoint at "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "http://localhost:11434/v1"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". This means any code written for the OpenAI Python client works with Ollama by changing only "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "base_url"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "api_key"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (any string works — the key is not validated locally)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from openai import OpenAI\n\n# Point the OpenAI client at the local Ollama daemon\nclient = OpenAI(\n    base_url=\"http://localhost:11434/v1\",\n    api_key=\"ollama\",  # required by the client but ignored by Ollama\n)\n\n# Now use the OpenAI API exactly as usual\nresponse = client.chat.completions.create(\n    model=\"llama3.2\",\n    messages=[\n        {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"You are a helpful assistant.\"},\n        {\"role\": \"user\",   \"content\": \"Explain monads in one paragraph.\"},\n    ],\n    temperature=0.7,\n    max_tokens=256,\n)\nprint(response.choices[0].message.content)\n\n# Streaming\nstream = client.chat.completions.create(\n    model=\"mistral\",\n    messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"Count to 5.\"}],\n    stream=True,\n)\nfor chunk in stream:\n    delta = chunk.choices[0].delta.content or \"\"\n    print(delta, end=\"\", flush=True)\n\n# Embeddings (models that support it)\nembedding_response = client.embeddings.create(\n    model=\"nomic-embed-text\",\n    input=\"The quick brown fox\",\n)\nvec = embedding_response.data[0].embedding\nprint(f\"Embedding dim: {len(vec)}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Async Usage"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nimport ollama\n\nasync def generate_parallel(\n    prompts: list[str],\n    model: str = \"llama3.2\",\n) -> list[str]:\n    \"\"\"Run multiple prompts concurrently against the local daemon.\"\"\"\n    client = ollama.AsyncClient()\n    async def one(prompt: str) -> str:\n        response = await client.generate(model=model, prompt=prompt)\n        return response[\"response\"]\n    return await asyncio.gather(*[one(p) for p in prompts])\n\n\nasync def stream_chat(model: str = \"llama3.2\") -> None:\n    client = ollama.AsyncClient()\n    messages = [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"Tell me a short story.\"}]\n    async for chunk in await client.chat(model=model, messages=messages, stream=True):\n        print(chunk[\"message\"][\"content\"], end=\"\", flush=True)\n\n\nasyncio.run(stream_chat())"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Modelfile: Customizing and Creating Models"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Modelfile"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is a Dockerfile-like spec that defines a custom model variant: a base model plus a system prompt, parameter overrides, and optionally a LoRA adapter. Once created, the model appears in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "ollama list"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and can be pulled by name like any other model."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Modelfile — save as ./Modelfile\nFROM llama3.2\n\n# System prompt baked into the model\nSYSTEM \"\"\"\nYou are a senior Python developer assistant. You respond with precise,\nrunnable Python code. You prefer built-in stdlib over third-party dependencies.\nYou always add type hints and a one-line docstring.\n\"\"\"\n\n# Default inference parameters\nPARAMETER temperature 0.1\nPARAMETER num_ctx 8192\nPARAMETER top_p 0.95\nPARAMETER stop \"<|im_end|>\"\nPARAMETER stop \"<|eot_id|>\"\n\n# Optional: a few-shot message history baked in\nMESSAGE user \"Write a function that reverses a string.\"\nMESSAGE assistant \"def reverse_string(s: str) -> str:\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"Reverse a string.\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    return s[::-1]\"\n\n# Build and use\n# ollama create py-assistant -f ./Modelfile\n# ollama run py-assistant"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import subprocess\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\ndef create_custom_model(\n    base_model: str,\n    model_name: str,\n    system_prompt: str,\n    temperature: float = 0.2,\n    context_length: int = 8192,\n    few_shots: list[dict] | None = None,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"\n    Programmatically create an Ollama custom model.\n\n    Args:\n        base_model: Ollama model tag to derive from (e.g. 'llama3.2').\n        model_name: Name for the new model.\n        system_prompt: System instruction baked into the model.\n        temperature: Default temperature parameter.\n        context_length: Context window size in tokens.\n        few_shots: Optional list of {role, content} messages.\n    \"\"\"\n    lines = [\n        f\"FROM {base_model}\",\n        f'SYSTEM \"\"\"{system_prompt}\"\"\"',\n        f\"PARAMETER temperature {temperature}\",\n        f\"PARAMETER num_ctx {context_length}\",\n    ]\n    if few_shots:\n        for msg in few_shots:\n            role = msg[\"role\"].lower()\n            content = msg[\"content\"].replace('\"', '\\\\\"')\n            lines.append(f'MESSAGE {role} \"{content}\"')\n\n    modelfile_path = Path(\"/tmp/ollama_modelfile\")\n    modelfile_path.write_text(\"\\n\\n\".join(lines) + \"\\n\")\n\n    result = subprocess.run(\n        [\"ollama\", \"create\", model_name, \"-f\", str(modelfile_path)],\n        capture_output=True, text=True\n    )\n    if result.returncode != 0:\n        raise RuntimeError(f\"ollama create failed: {result.stderr}\")\n    print(f\"Created model: {model_name}\")\n\n\ncreate_custom_model(\n    base_model=\"llama3.2\",\n    model_name=\"sql-assistant\",\n    system_prompt=(\n        \"You are a SQL expert. Write standard SQL that runs on PostgreSQL 16. \"\n        \"Always include comments for complex joins. Never use SELECT *.\"\n    ),\n    temperature=0.0,\n    context_length=16384,\n)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "GPU Configuration and Performance Tuning"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ollama auto-detects CUDA and Metal and offloads as many model layers to VRAM as possible. The key tuning levers are context length (directly proportional to VRAM usage) and quantization level (the model tag)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# VRAM usage = model weights + KV cache\n# KV cache grows with context length: ~2 * num_layers * num_heads * head_dim * ctx * 2 bytes\n# For llama3.2:3b at 4096 context: ~0.2 GB KV cache + 2 GB weights ≈ 2.2 GB VRAM\n# For llama3.2:3b at 32768 context: ~1.6 GB KV cache + 2 GB weights ≈ 3.6 GB VRAM\n\n# Available quantization levels (lower = smaller + faster, slightly less accurate)\n# Q2_K  ~35% of fp16 size  (very low quality — avoid for instruction following)\n# Q4_K_M ~55% of fp16 size  (good default — reasonable quality/size trade-off)\n# Q6_K  ~75% of fp16 size  (near-fp16 quality)\n# Q8_0  ~95% of fp16 size  (essentially lossless)\n\n# Pull specific quantization\nollama pull llama3.2:3b-q4_K_M    # 4-bit quantization, medium version\nollama pull llama3.2:3b-q8_0      # 8-bit quantization\n\n# Environment variables for GPU control\nexport OLLAMA_NUM_GPU=1            # number of GPUs to use\nexport OLLAMA_GPU_OVERHEAD=0       # reserve VRAM headroom (bytes)\nexport OLLAMA_MAX_LOADED_MODELS=1  # models to keep warm (default 1)\nexport OLLAMA_NUM_PARALLEL=4       # concurrent request slots\n\n# Check what Ollama detected\nollama show llama3.2 --verbose"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Drop-In Replacement for Development"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A common pattern is to use Ollama for local development and integration testing, then swap to a cloud provider for production — controlled by an environment variable. The OpenAI-compatible endpoint makes this seamless."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import os\nfrom openai import OpenAI\n\ndef get_llm_client() -> tuple[OpenAI, str]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Return (client, model) configured for the current environment.\n    Set LLM_BACKEND=ollama for local dev; leave unset for OpenAI production.\n    \"\"\"\n    backend = os.environ.get(\"LLM_BACKEND\", \"openai\")\n    if backend == \"ollama\":\n        return (\n            OpenAI(\n                base_url=\"http://localhost:11434/v1\",\n                api_key=\"ollama\",\n            ),\n            os.environ.get(\"OLLAMA_MODEL\", \"llama3.2\"),\n        )\n    return (\n        OpenAI(api_key=os.environ[\"OPENAI_API_KEY\"]),\n        os.environ.get(\"OPENAI_MODEL\", \"gpt-4o-mini\"),\n    )\n\n\ndef summarize(text: str) -> str:\n    client, model = get_llm_client()\n    response = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=model,\n        messages=[\n            {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"Summarize the following text in 2-3 sentences.\"},\n            {\"role\": \"user\",   \"content\": text},\n        ],\n        max_tokens=200,\n        temperature=0.3,\n    )\n    return response.choices[0].message.content\n\n\n# Usage: LLM_BACKEND=ollama python app.py\n# In CI / production: LLM_BACKEND unset → OpenAI"
          }
        ]
      },
